Signature:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a positive rational number then v0 is an object)

Signature:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a positive rational number and v1 is a positive rational number then for all v2, (if v2 is equal to v1 \cdot v0 then v2 is a positive rational number)))

Axiom:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a positive rational number and v1 is a positive rational number then v1 \cdot v0 is equal to v0 \cdot v1))

Axiom:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v0 is a positive rational number and v1 is a positive rational number and v2 is a positive rational number then v1 \cdot v0 \cdot v2 is equal to v1 \cdot v0 \cdot v2)))

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a positive rational number then ((v0 is left cancellative) iff for all v1, (for all v2, (if v1 is a positive rational number and v2 is a positive rational number then (if v0 \cdot v2 is equal to v0 \cdot v1 then v2 is equal to v1)))))

Axiom:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a positive rational number then v0 is left cancellative)

Signature:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is a positive rational number)

Signature:
  for all v0, (if v0 is equal to 1 then v0 is a natural number)

Axiom:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number then v1 \cdot v0 is a natural number))

Definition:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number then ((v1 \mid v0) iff for some v2, (v2 is a natural number and v2 \cdot v1 is equal to v0))))

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then ((v0 is prime) iff (it is wrong that (v0 is equal to 1) and for all v1, (for all v2, (if v1 is a natural number and v2 is a natural number then (if v0 \mid v2 \cdot v1 then (v0 \mid v2 or v0 \mid v1)))))))

Definition:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number then ((v1 and v0 are coprime) iff it is wrong that (for some v2, (v2 is a natural number and v2 \mid v1 and v2 \mid v0 and v2 is prime)))))

Axiom:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a positive rational number then for some v1, (for some v2, (v1 is a natural number and v2 is a natural number and (v1 and v2 are coprime and v1 \cdot v0 is equal to v2))))

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number and v0 is prime then for all v1, (if v1 is a positive rational number then it is wrong that (v1 \cdot v1 is equal to v0)))
Proof:
  it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
  q is a positive rational number and p is equal to q \cdot q
  m is a natural number and n is a natural number and (m and n are coprime and m \cdot q is equal to n)
  p \cdot m \cdot m is equal to n \cdot n
  p \mid n
  k is a natural number and n is equal to k \cdot p
  p \cdot m \cdot m is equal to p \cdot k \cdot n
  m \cdot m is equal to p \cdot k \cdot k
  p \mid m
  falsity holds
Qed.

